## Priorities

- **Navigability and core user journeys** over completeness.
- **Stubbed or local dummy data** (JSON, in-memory, or mocked handlers). No obligation to match a real backend schema until design locks.
- **Clear labeling** where things are provisional: short comments (`// wireframe`), placeholder copy, or UI badges like “Prototype” when it helps stakeholders.

## De-prioritize (unless the user asks)

- Production auth, real APIs, full validation, accessibility audits to WCAG AAA, performance tuning, and hardening.
- Pixel-perfect fidelity or final branding before **product** visual design is locked. In this case, prefer **clear hierarchy and spacing** (colors still follow Flexoki per `ui.mdc`) so the layout is critique-ready.

## When adding behavior

- Prefer the **simplest** state (local state, URL params, or a tiny context) that makes the flow clickable.
- If a flow is undecided, implement a **stub screen** (“Not in scope for this prototype”) rather than guessing final product behavior.

## Visual language (UI work)

When implementing screens, components, or styles, follow **`.cursor/rules/ui.mdc`** for wireframe UI patterns and the **required [Flexoki](https://stephango.com/flexoki)** color system. This rule defines scope and priorities; `ui.mdc` defines how the prototype should look and behave in the frontend.

## Data and copy

- Use **obvious fake** names, dates, and numbers so testers know it is not real.
- For file layout, mocks, and toggles, follow **`.cursor/rules/dummy-data.mdc`** when editing matching source files.
